03753nam a22005655i 9780520925076DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20022002cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209250767 a10.1525/97805209250762doi  a(DE-B1597)519620  a(OCoLC)51821772  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aBM755.E6bE8513 2002eb 7aHIS0370102bisacsh04a296.8/32/0922211 aEtkes, Immanuel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Gaon of Vilna :bThe Man and His Image /cImmanuel Etkes. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2002] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aS. Mark Taper Foundation Imprint in Jewish Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Ha-Gaon He-Hasid: In His Own Time and for Succeeding Generations -- t2. The Vilna Gaon and Haskalah -- t3. The Vilna Gaon and the Beginning of the Struggle against Hasidism -- t4. The Vilna Gaon and the Mitnagdim as Seen by the Hasidim -- t5. Rabbi Ḥayyim of Volozhin's Response to Hasidism -- t6. Talmudic Scholarship and the Rabbinate in Lithuanian Jewry during the Nineteenth Century -- t7. Torah and Yira in the Thought and Practice of the Vilna Gaon -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA legendary figure in his own lifetime, Rabbi Eliahu ben Shlomo Zalman (1720-1797) was known as the "Gaon of Vilna." He was the acknowledged master of Talmudic studies in the vibrant intellectual center of Vilna, revered throughout Eastern Europe for his learning and his ability to traverse with ease seemingly opposed domains of thought and activity. After his death, the myth that had been woven around him became even more powerful and was expressed in various public images. The formation of these images was influenced as much by the needs and wishes of those who clung to and depended on them as by the actual figure of the Gaon. In this penetrating study, Immanuel Etkes sheds light on aspects of the Vilna Gaon's "real" character and traces several public images of him as they have developed and spread from the early nineteenth century until the present.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aHasidismxHistoryx18th century. 0aHasidismxHistoryy18th century. 0aRabbisxBiographyxLithuaniaxVilnius. 0aRabbiszLithuaniazVilniusvBiography. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520925076423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520925076.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles